We have \(2p^2+8p+5=0\).  Using the quadratic formula \(p=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\) with \(a=2,\;b=8,\;c=5\) gives

\[
p=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{8^2-4\cdot2\cdot5}}{2\cdot2}
=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{64-40}}{4}
=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{24}}{4}
=\frac{-8\pm2\sqrt6}{4}
=\frac{-4\pm\sqrt6}{2}.
\]

So the two solutions are 
\[
p=\frac{-4+\sqrt6}{2}
\quad\text{and}\quad
p=\frac{-4-\sqrt6}{2}.
\]

Here, \(a=5\), \(b=-11\), \(c=3\).  The quadratic formula gives
\[
q = \frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}
   = \frac{-(-11)\pm\sqrt{(-11)^2-4\cdot5\cdot3}}{2\cdot5}
   = \frac{11\pm\sqrt{121-60}}{10}
   = \frac{11\pm\sqrt{61}}{10}.
\]
So the two solutions are
\[
q = \frac{11+\sqrt{61}}{10}
\quad\text{or}\quad
q = \frac{11-\sqrt{61}}{10}.
\]

Using the quadratic formula \(m=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\) with \(a=3,\;b=12,\;c=7\) gives

\[
m=\frac{-12\pm\sqrt{12^2-4\cdot3\cdot7}}{2\cdot3}
=\frac{-12\pm\sqrt{144-84}}{6}
=\frac{-12\pm\sqrt{60}}{6}
=\frac{-12\pm2\sqrt{15}}{6}
=\frac{-6\pm\sqrt{15}}{3}.
\]

So the two solutions are
\[
m=\frac{-6+\sqrt{15}}{3}
\quad\text{and}\quad
m=\frac{-6-\sqrt{15}}{3}.
\]
